node.text:
Dogs trained for detecting smells are being taught a new scent: COVID-19. ⁠
⁠
Two specially trained dogs, Cobra and One Betta, are part of a pilot program out of Miami International Airport that inspects employees. A month into the program, the dogs have detected two cases: One staff member tested positive while the other was recovering from COVID-19. The project launched the last week of August and has been extended to October, thanks to a partnership between the Miami-Dade Aviation Department, Global Forensic and Justice Center, and Florida International University. Dr. Kenneth Furton, provost and executive vice president of Florida International University, hopes the success will continue. According to Furton, the dogs are 97.5% accurate in detecting the virus.⁠
⁠
⁠

node.text:
'The number of resignations received leaves us no choice but to pause delivering babies.'⁠
⁠
The fight between vaccine mandates and health care workers at Lewis County General Hospital in Lowville, NY, is severely impacting other departments like the hospital's maternity ward and newborn nursery, said CEO Gerald Cayer, forcing them to pause baby deliveries after September 24.⁠
⁠
Cayer says dozens of hospital workers have resigned over vaccine mandates for health care workers, both at the state level and soon-to-be federal level. Under the state deadline, health care workers have until September 27 to get their first shot.⁠
⁠
According to Cayer, 165 employees are still unvaccinated, and it's 'not clear what they will do.' The vaccination rate is currently 73% in the Lewis County Health System. If more resignations continue, Cayer says additional departments could be greatly impacted.⁠
⁠
On Thursday, President Joe Biden imposed new vaccine rules. Under the new rules, 17 million health care workers at facilities that receive Medicare or Medicaid funding must be fully vaccinated.⁠
⁠
⁠
